edback\": \"Atmospheric Spark Discharge Route aligns with Parker et al. (2011); however, it is a single-step, low-selectivity, low-yield process and does not clarify mechanistic details. Useful for highlighting environmental diversity, but not robust for high-yield network design.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Note that serine yields may be trace/ambiguous; mechanistic steps could be detailed for deeper analysis.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 1.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.9,\n      \"feedback\": \"Interstellar Ice Photolysis Route uses robust experimental backing (Bernstein et al. 2002), producing racemic serine via UV and hydrolysis. No mechanistic content in Earth's environments, but solid for modeling exogenous sources.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly link this route to integration with surface concentrating/cycling steps.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 1.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"Hydrothermal-to-Glycolonitrile Route models the sequential conversion to glycolaldehyde, feeding into cyanide-dependent steps. Glycolonitrile as a prebiotic intermediate is well-supported. Environmental and mechanistic logic consistent with literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify mineral- or clay-facilitated concentration for weakly stable species as a minor improvement.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 1.0,\n        \"rxn_005\": 1.0,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.98,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.96,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.97,\n      \"target_achievement\": 1.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.97,\n      \"feedback\": \"Bisulfite-Glycolaldehyde Route with Concentration Cycling most stringently aligns with experimental work (Ritson & Sutherland, Nature Comm 2018), integrating protection/trapping, mineral cycling, and aminonitrile conversion. Mechanistically and environmentally robust.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Great modeling. Could optionally further discuss the effect of pH and mineral saturation; otherwise exemplary.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 1.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.94,\n      \"feedback\": \"Photoredox Glycolonitrile Route is highly plausible and in line with literature photochemistry (Ritson & Sutherland 2012; Patel et al. 2015). HCN/aldehyde chemistry converging to aminonitrile is experimentally founded. All connections are justified.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.7\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.7,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.6,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.7,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.7,\n      \"feedback\": \"Theoretical Glycine-Formaldehyde Coupling is based on computational speculation (Li et al. 2024, JACS Au), with high activation barriers, no experimental confirmation under prebiotic conditions, and poorly established environmental context. Not currently robust as a prebiotic pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"This route should be treated as highly speculative unless further supported by laboratory data.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.97,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This synthesis network is an exemplary implementation with strong literature alignment, robust environmental logic, hub convergence, and node connectivity. All key intermediates from deep research are included. The network spans all major pathways currently supported by prebiotic literature, including both 'protected' (bisulfite/formamide) and unprotected Strecker/photoredox systems, as well as exogenous sources. Minor suggestions would further fortify environmental realism, especially around explicit mineral phase assignments and cycling details, but such absence does not substantially detract from network quality. All major bottlenecks and challenges discussed in research (stability, concentration, redundancy by parallel architecture) are addressed. Only the purely theoretical glycine-formaldehyde coupling route (P10) is not robust; all others are plausible and in many cases experimentally verified. Hub molecules have high degree, the network is highly convergent, and environmental interconnections are seamless.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 1.0,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 1.0\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_005": 1.0, "rxn_008": 0.95}, "chemical_feasi